1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,780
Let's take a look at this webpage now to learn more about APIs.

2
00:00:03,780 --> 00:00:07,950
First, I'd like to show you how I can manually get the metadata of a particular book.

3
00:00:07,950 --> 00:00:12,180
Right now I just navigated to the webpage I shared earlier in my browser.

4
00:00:12,180 --> 00:00:14,640
Take a look at a small snippet of

5
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:18,075
the JSON file containing the metadata we can get from these pages.

6
00:00:18,075 --> 00:00:20,190
We have some great info available,

7
00:00:20,190 --> 00:00:22,545
including when the book was created,

8
00:00:22,545 --> 00:00:24,660
the different files available, etc.

9
00:00:24,660 --> 00:00:25,920
At the end of the file,

10
00:00:25,920 --> 00:00:30,495
we can actually see information including the reviews, etc.

11
00:00:30,495 --> 00:00:33,375
Now, there are two primary ways to use APIs,

12
00:00:33,375 --> 00:00:35,040
and they're nicely illustrated by

13
00:00:35,040 --> 00:00:38,230
the developer tools that the Internet Archive has put out there.

14
00:00:38,230 --> 00:00:40,160
Let's go ahead and switch over to

15
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:43,180
a Jupyter Notebook to figure out how to wrangle this data.

16
00:00:43,180 --> 00:00:47,765
One approach to use APIs is similar to what we've done with the request library,

17
00:00:47,765 --> 00:00:49,820
where we make an HTTP GET request.

18
00:00:49,820 --> 00:00:53,540
This method enables us to retrieve the desired data directly from

19
00:00:53,540 --> 00:00:55,700
the API by sending a request and

20
00:00:55,700 --> 00:00:58,700
receiving a response containing the relevant information.

21
00:00:58,700 --> 00:01:01,775
First, let's go ahead and import our requests and

22
00:01:01,775 --> 00:01:05,815
Python's inbuilt JSON library to save the JSON file we're going to get.

23
00:01:05,815 --> 00:01:08,510
Let's create a HTTP GET request with

24
00:01:08,510 --> 00:01:12,020
the request library to retrieve metadata from this particular books URL.

25
00:01:12,020 --> 00:01:16,780
The books unique identifier is specified after the metadata tag.

26
00:01:16,780 --> 00:01:20,810
The retrieved information is stored in an object called Book.

27
00:01:20,810 --> 00:01:22,430
Now, if we run this code,

28
00:01:22,430 --> 00:01:26,465
we see that Book is primarily containing the response code,

29
00:01:26,465 --> 00:01:29,670
amongst other data and methods.

30
00:01:29,720 --> 00:01:36,925
We then check for any exceptions that requests is raising using raise for status.

31
00:01:36,925 --> 00:01:40,280
See, we're seeing here that it doesn't really raise any exceptions,

32
00:01:40,280 --> 00:01:41,900
so we can go ahead and proceed.

33
00:01:41,900 --> 00:01:44,420
Next, we convert the JSON formatted data from

34
00:01:44,420 --> 00:01:48,590
the API response into a native Python data structure using dot-json.

35
00:01:48,590 --> 00:01:51,560
The convert data is then assigned to a variable,

36
00:01:51,560 --> 00:01:53,820
in this case, JSON data.

37
00:01:53,830 --> 00:01:56,870
Now, here we can see that the JSON data

38
00:01:56,870 --> 00:01:59,840
variable is containing the metadata of the book we selected,

39
00:01:59,840 --> 00:02:02,710
which we previously saw as part of the webpage.

40
00:02:02,710 --> 00:02:05,060
Now that we have all of this great data,

41
00:02:05,060 --> 00:02:07,445
let's go ahead and save our JSON file.

42
00:02:07,445 --> 00:02:11,480
We'll open the file path in book.json in write mode and define

43
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:16,250
the file object as f. We're then going to use the json.dump

44
00:02:16,250 --> 00:02:18,890
function to save the data into the

45
00:02:18,890 --> 00:02:23,135
book.json file by specifying the JSON data variable in the file object

46
00:02:23,135 --> 00:02:26,840
f. Note that the Internet Archive

47
00:02:26,840 --> 00:02:31,055
API does not require any authentication for users to retrieve metadata.

48
00:02:31,055 --> 00:02:35,410
But some APIs may require authentication through an HTTP post method.

49
00:02:35,410 --> 00:02:37,055
In that case, in addition to this,

50
00:02:37,055 --> 00:02:40,700
you're actually required to provide your username and password for an account

51
00:02:40,700 --> 00:02:45,235
you created with the website in order to be able to make a GET request for the data.

52
00:02:45,235 --> 00:02:47,850
Let's talk about a second approach.

53
00:02:47,850 --> 00:02:50,315
Now, the second approach to use APIs is using

54
00:02:50,315 --> 00:02:54,350
a customized developer library for that particular data source if available.

55
00:02:54,350 --> 00:02:56,825
For example, the Internet Archive has created

56
00:02:56,825 --> 00:02:59,890
an Internet Archive library for using its API.

57
00:02:59,890 --> 00:03:02,265
Here's a small snippet from their tutorials.

58
00:03:02,265 --> 00:03:04,330
Here you can import get_item,

59
00:03:04,330 --> 00:03:07,760
to retrieve the metadata of the item associated with the identifier,

60
00:03:07,760 --> 00:03:09,860
and then store it in an object called book,

61
00:03:09,860 --> 00:03:12,505
as we're doing here with our Language of Flowers book.

62
00:03:12,505 --> 00:03:14,900
Then we can go ahead and iterate through

63
00:03:14,900 --> 00:03:18,320
the key value pairs in the metadata attribute of the book object.

64
00:03:18,320 --> 00:03:22,520
We can use dot items on the book's metadata because that is what contains

65
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:26,765
the key value pair as tuples in a list that we can then iterate through.

66
00:03:26,765 --> 00:03:31,580
We can then print each key value pair to get the metadata of the book in a neat format.

67
00:03:31,580 --> 00:03:34,225
How do you decide which option to use?

68
00:03:34,225 --> 00:03:36,890
HTTP GET request is not always available,

69
00:03:36,890 --> 00:03:38,390
particularly when a website or

70
00:03:38,390 --> 00:03:41,630
a data source provider prohibits gathering through these means,

71
00:03:41,630 --> 00:03:44,420
due to concerns like an overload of requests being sent to

72
00:03:44,420 --> 00:03:47,585
the website or the website simply doesn't respond.

73
00:03:47,585 --> 00:03:51,440
Using customized libraries is typically a more popular option,

74
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:55,550
as popular websites typically have their own library to work with their API,

75
00:03:55,550 --> 00:03:57,710
as we saw with the Internet Archive.

76
00:03:57,710 --> 00:04:01,370
Some other providers who have customized libraries are Wikipedia,

77
00:04:01,370 --> 00:04:04,170
Twitter, or Spotify, and more.

